  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious criminal offense under federal law in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The primary statute governing money laundering is the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, codified at **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**. The penalties depend on the specific provision violated, the amount of money involved, and other aggravating factors. Below are the key penalties:\n\n### 1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments)**\n   - **Maximum Penalty**: Up to **20 years in federal prison**.\n   - **Fines**: Up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - **Additional Penalties**: Forfeiture of property involved in or traceable to the money laundering offense.\n\n   This section applies to individuals who knowingly conduct or attempt to conduct financial transactions involving proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to promote criminal activity, conceal the nature of the proceeds, or evade reporting requirements.\n\n### 2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Unlawful Activity)**\n   - **Maximum Penalty**: Up to **10 years in federal prison**.\n   - **Fines**: Up to **$250,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - **Additional Penalties**: Forfeiture of property involved in or traceable to the offense.\n\n   This section applies to individuals who knowingly engage in transactions involving criminally derived property valued at more than $10,000.\n\n### 3. **Enhanced Penalties**\n   - **Terrorism Financing**: If the money laundering is connected to terrorism, penalties may include **life imprisonment**.\n   - **Repeat Offenders**: Enhanced penalties may apply for repeat offenders or if the offense involves large sums of money or significant criminal activity.\n\n### 4. **Civil Penalties**\n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities may face **civil forfeiture** of assets involved in money laundering.\n   - Civil penalties can include fines and other sanctions imposed by regulatory agencies such as the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**.\n\n### 5. **Additional Consequences**\n   - **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize and forfeit assets linked to money laundering.\n   - **Reputational Damage**: Individuals and businesses convicted of money laundering may face lasting reputational harm.\n   - **Loss of Professional Licenses**: Professionals (e.g., lawyers, accountants, financial advisors) may lose their licenses or certifications.\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors such as the scale of the operation, the defendant\u2019s role, and whether the case involves international or organized crime. Prosecutors often pursue **conspiracy charges** under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 371**, which can increase penalties further.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
